# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cinema-politica
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin, which means "pathfinder", was born on August 31, 1932, near Lebanon, New Hampshire.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] When she was six months old, her family returned to the Odanak reserve located near Sorel, Quebec, where she lived until she was nine years old.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her mother ran a boarding house and her father was a medicine maker and a guide.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] During this period they lived with her maternal aunt Jesse Benedict, her husband Levi Benedict, and their own six children.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Théophile Panadis, her mother's cousin, initiated Obomsawin into the history of the Abenaki Nation and taught her many songs and legends.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] When she was nine years old, Obomsawin and her parents left Odanak for Trois-Rivières, where they were the only Indigenous family.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] At that time speaking Obomsawin spoke little French and no English.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her father died of tuberculosis when she was twelve.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] During a two-year stay in Florida she also learned English.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In the late 1950s she moved back to Montreal and began performing as a singer and a storyteller, making appearances on reservations, in prisons and schools, and at music festivals.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her daughter, Kisos Obomsawin, was born in 1969.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 1960, she debuted as a singer during a concert at The Town Hall in New York City.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] As a performer Obomsawin has toured Canada, the United States, and Europe performing for humanitarian causes in universities, museums, prisons, art centres, and folk art festivals.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] She managed her own stage at the Mariposa Folk Festival in the 1960s.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her 1988 album *Bush Lady* featured traditional songs of the Abenaki people, as well as original compositions.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Originally released on her own private press, it was remastered and re-released in 2018 by Constellation Records.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] As of 2025, Obomsawin has directed 65 films with the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin's filmmaking came to the attention of the National Film Board of Canada in the mid-1960s, when she held fundraising concerts to pay for the construction of a swimming pool in Odanak.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Children in her community were no longer able to swim in the Saint Francis River, but were not allowed to use a pool in a neighboring community which was for white residents only.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin was interviewed about her film about the issue in a report for CBC-TV's *Telescope* series, which was seen by NFB producers Joe Koenig and Bob Verrall.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] They invited her to work as an advisor on a film about First Nations people.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin directed her first documentary for the NFB, *Christmas at Moose Factory*, in 1971.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] She made a series of films about the 1990 Oka crisis.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] The first, *Kanehsatake: 270 Years of Resistance* (1993), is a feature-length film documenting the 1990 Kanien'kehá:ka uprising in Kanehsatà:ke and Oka.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] It was followed by *My Name is Kahentiiosta* (1995), a film about a young Kahnawake woman who was arrested after the 78-day armed standoff, and *Spudwrench – Kahnawake Man* (1997), profiling Randy Horne, a high-steel worker from Kahnawake.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] The 2000 NFB release *Rocks at Whiskey Trench* was Obomsawin's fourth film in her series about the Oka crisis.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] The Esgenoôpetitj First Nation in New Brunswick was the subject of her 2002 documentary, *Is the Crown at War With Us?*, exploring a conflict with the Department of Fisheries and non-Indigenous fishers over fishing rights.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her 2003 NFB documentary *Our Nationhood* chronicles the Listuguj Mi'gmaq First Nation's efforts to use and manage the natural resources of their traditional lands.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 2005, Obomsawin completed her short drama *Sigwan*, following a young girl who is aided by the animals of the forest.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 2006, she completed *WABAN-AKI: People from Where the Sun Rises,* a look at the people and stories from her home reserve of Odanak.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her credits also include *Gene Boy Came Home* (2007)*,* about First Nations Vietnam War veteran Eugene Benedict.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 2009, she completed the documentary *Professor Norman Cornett: "Since when do we divorce the right answer from an honest answer?",* looking at the dismissal of McGill University religious studies lecturer Norman Cornett, which had its world premiere at the Hot Docs film festival.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 2010, Obomsawin completed the short drama *When All the Leaves Are Gone*, about her experiences attending public school in Quebec.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her 2012 documentary *The People of the Kattawapiskak River* on the Attawapiskat housing-crisis was conceived when Obomsawin was present in the community in 2011, working on another film for the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin's 2013 documentary *Hi-Ho Mistahey!* about Shannen Koostachin, a First Nations education activist, premiered at the 2013 Toronto International Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin's 2014 documentary *Trick or Treaty?* was the first film by an Indigenous filmmaker to screen in the Masters program at the Toronto International Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin began conceptualizing the film in 2010 when she was invited by Stan Louttit, Grand Chief of the Mushkegowuk Council, to film a conference the band was hosting regarding Treaty 9.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her 2016 documentary *We Can't Make the Same Mistake Twice* explored a human rights complaint filed against the Canadian government over discrimination against First Nations children.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] It had its world premiere on September 13 at the 2016 Toronto International Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her documentary film *Our People Will Be Healed*, about the Helen Betty Osborne Ininiw Education Resource Centre in Norway House Cree Nation, premiered in the Masters program of the 2017 Toronto International Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin has also taught at the Summer Institute of Film and Television in Ottawa.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin has served on the jury at numerous Canadian film festivals throughout her career, including the Toronto International Film Festival, Hot Docs, the imagineNATIVE Film and Media Arts Festival, and the Regina International Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] For more than 25 years, Obomsawin has worked as an engraver and printmaker, with exhibitions in Canada and Europe.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Mother and child imagery is prominent in her work, which also combines material from her own dreams with animal spirits and historical events.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Her work was exhibited at the Maison Lacombe in Quebec in 2007.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In March 2001, Obomsawin received a Governor General's Award in Visual and Media Arts.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] A retrospective of her work was held from May 14 to 26 of 2008 at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] That same month, she received the Governor General's Performing Arts Award for Lifetime Artistic Achievement.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In the spring of 2009, Obomsawin was honoured with a special retrospective at Hot Docs and received the festival's Hot Docs Outstanding Achievement Award.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 2010, she was named to the *Playback* Canadian Film & Television Hall of Fame.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin was named an Honorary Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada for 2013.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In January of that year, the Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television announced that Obomsawin would receive its Humanitarian Award for Exceptional Contributions to Community & Public Service, presented at the 2nd Canadian Screen Awards.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] At the 2013 Toronto International Film Festival, she was a recipient of a Birks Diamond Tribute to the Year's Women in Film.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In October 2015, she received a lifetime achievement award from Chile's Valdivia International Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In February 2015, the Montreal-based peace advocacy arts group Artistes pour la paix presented her with its lifetime achievement award.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In March of that year, she was among the first 35 people named to the inaugural Ordre des arts et des lettres du Québec.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In March 2017, she received the inaugural Prix Origine at Montreal's Bâtisseuses de la Cité Awards for her work on Indigenous issues.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 2018, she was named a Commander of the Order of Montreal.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In June 2019 she was named a Companion of the Order of Canada after previously having been named Officer in 2002.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] At the 2019 Vancouver International Film Festival, Obomsawin received the Best Canadian Documentary Award for *Jordan River Anderson, the Messenger*.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In October 2020 she was named the thirteenth laureate of the Glenn Gould Prize.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Also in 2020 she received the Iris Tribute lifetime honour at the 22nd Quebec Cinema Awards from Québec Cinéma's Comité de représentation professionnelle.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] At the 2021 Toronto International Film Festival, a special retrospective program of Obomsawsin's films was presented.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin was named as that year's recipient of TIFF's Jeff Skoll Award in Impact Media.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] In 2023, Obomsawin was the recipient of the 63rd Edward MacDowell Medal, becoming the first awardee from the Indigenous land on which the residency program is located.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Obomsawin has chaired the board of directors of the Native Women's Shelter of Montreal and sat on the Canada Council's First People's Advisory Board.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] She was a board member of Studio One, the NFB's Indigenous-led studio, and a former advisor to the New Initiatives in Film, a Studio D program for women of color and First Nations women.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] As a member of the board of Aboriginal Voices Radio Network, Obomsawin was part of an initiative to obtain a radio licence for the organization.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] A lifetime member of the board of directors for the Aboriginal Peoples Television Network, Obomsawin is also a member of the board for Vermont Public Television and National Geographic International.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Cinema Politica created the Alanis Obomsawin Award for Commitment to Community and Resistance in 2011.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] The ImagineNATIVE Film and Media Arts Festival presents the Documentary Feature Award in honour of Alanis Obomsawin every year.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] Festival Regard's Regards Autochtones Prize was renamed the Alanis Obomsawin Prize in her honour in 2025.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] From February to April 2022, the Haus der Kulturen der Welt dedicated the exhibition *The Children Have to Hear Another Story – Alanis Obomsawin* to her.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] The catalogue *Alanis Obomsawin: Lifework* was produced on the occasion of the exhibition.
[src:cinema-politica/alanis-obomsawin] From April to August 2023, the Vancouver Art Gallery held the same exhibition.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The **Canada Council for the Arts** (French: *Conseil des arts du Canada*), commonly called the **Canada Council**, is a Crown corporation established in 1957 as an arts council of the Government of Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] It is Canada's public arts funder, with a mandate to foster and promote the study and enjoyment of, and the production of works in, the arts.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Council's grants, services, initiatives, prizes and payments contribute to the vibrancy of a creative and diverse arts and literary scene and support its presence across Canada and abroad.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Council's investments contribute to fostering greater engagement in the arts among Canadians and international audiences.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In addition, the Canada Council administers the Art Bank, which operates art rental programs and an exhibitions and outreach program.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council Art Bank holds the largest collection of contemporary Canadian art in the world.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council is also responsible for the secretariat for the Canadian Commission for UNESCO and the Public Lending Right Commission.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council for the Arts is an arms-length organization based in Ottawa, Ontario, that reports to Parliament through the Minister of Canadian Heritage.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Its endowment income is supplemented by annual appropriations from Parliament, donations, and bequests.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Its main duty is allotting grants and prizes to Canadian artists based on the merits of their applications.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council also funds and administers many of Canada's top arts awards, including the Governor General's Literary Awards and the Governor General's Awards in Visual and Media Arts.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council is called from time to time to appear before parliamentary committees, particularly the Canadian House of Commons Standing Committee on Canadian Heritage.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Its accounts are audited by the Auditor General of Canada and included in an Annual Report to Parliament.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] "In 1977, the Canada Council sets up the Payment for Public Use Committee to discuss the creation of a Public Lending Right (PLR) program.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The first version of the *Canada Council for the Arts Act* was titled *An Act for the Establishment of a Canada Council for the Encouragement of the Arts, Humanities and Social Sciences*.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] It was assented to on March 28, 1957, by the 22nd federal parliament under Liberal Prime Minister Louis St.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] This version of the Act established a council of 21 members who could serve between three and five years, depending on their role in the Council.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Act also granted them the power to co-operate with organizations who had similar aims (such as universities) in funding and facilitating work in the Arts, Humanities, and Social Sciences across Canada, as well as promoting Canadian work in these fields abroad.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] There were several amendments over the years, with most being minor alterations to language or the status of Council members for tax purposes.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Two major amendments, passed in the 1970s and later the 1990s, were more significant.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 1976–77, an amendment renamed the Act to simply the Canada Council Act.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In conjunction with the establishment of the Social Science and Humanities Research Council, the Act narrowed the Council's mandate exclusively to "the study and enjoyment of, and the production of works in, the arts".
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] While the council's powers as a promoting and sponsoring body remained, all references to social sciences and humanities were removed.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 1992, this was reversed, and duties of the Research Council, as well as promotional activities of the Department of External Affairs, were reabsorbed into the Canada Council.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] This amendment also reduced the number of mandatory Council meetings to two, and shortened the deadline for the Council to submit its financial audits.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The *Canada Council for the Arts Act* was last amended in 2009.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Between 2002 and 2009 were a number of small revisions to get to the modern *Act* that we have today.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The majority of the changes to the *Canada Council for the Arts Act* since 2002 involve updates to language due to evolving definitions.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] For example, in section 12 of Objects, Powers and Duties of the Council 'public service of Canada' from 2002 was updated to 'federal public administration' as of 2005.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] However, one of the most significant changes concerns Part 4 – Members of the Council.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In the major 2002 Amendment other members of the council who were not the Chairperson or Vice-Chairperson would be appointed for a period of three years.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2006 this was updated and changed to a period of four years and has remained fours years since, up to and including the current version.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Another significant change is the loss of council members.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Instead of 21 council members, in the modern *Act* there is the Chairperson and Vice-Chairperson along with 9 other members of the council.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] That is a reduction of 10 members since the 1977 version of the Act.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council for the Arts, as a federal Crown corporation, is accountable to Parliament through the Minister of Canadian Heritage and is governed by an 11-member Board.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Board is composed of a Chair, Vice-Chair, and nine other members from across Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Along with the Director and CEO, Board members are appointed by the Governor-in-Council for fixed terms.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Board meets at least three times per year and is responsible for the oversight of the Canada Council's policies, programs, budgets, and grant decisions.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council's Executive Management, on the other hand—which is led by the Director and CEO—is responsible for establishing and implementing the broad directions and vision developed by the Board, as well as managing the Council itself.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Director is appointed by the Governor in Council as well, and also acts as the chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council for the Arts was established and began operations in 1957 as part of a major recommendation of the 1951 report by the Royal Commission on National Development in the Arts, Letters and Sciences, commonly known as the Massey Commission.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] As such, the report recommended that the Government of Canada establish a **Canada Council for the Encouragement of the Arts, Letters, Humanities and Social Sciences**.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Due to "the dangers inherent in any system of subvention by the central government to the arts and letters and to the culture of the country generally," the Commission—operating in the aftermath of WWII—proposed that the new council be created with a large amount of independence from government.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council for the Arts was thereafter created as an independent, arm's-length body, accountable to Parliament through the Minister of Canadian Heritage with responsibility for establishing its priorities, policies, and funding programs as well as making grant decisions.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In its first year, from an initial endowment of CA$50 million, the Council had a budget of $1.5 million for the arts, humanities, and social sciences.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] By 1964, the Council proposed for a substantial increase to the endowment.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Instead, the Council's main source of revenue became yearly government appropriations.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 1977, the Canada Council sets up the Payment for Public Use Committee to discuss the creation of a Public Lending Right (PLR) program.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The following year, the federal government created the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council, adopting responsibility for the humanities and social sciences from the Canada Council, which would now only be responsible for the arts.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In March 1986, the Payment for Public Use (PPU) program was established by a Cabinet decision, with an initial budget of $3 million allocated to it by the Treasury Board Secretariat.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] This would make Canada the 13th country in the world to develop a PLR program.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The initial name was promptly changed to Public Lending Right, and catalogue-based system was adopted.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The mid-1990s "program review" process, which the federal government undertook to curb spending and reduce the deficit, affected the Canada Council as it did other federal agencies and departments.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] During the mid-1990s period, the Council was restructured and its staff numbers reduced.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Toward the end of the decade, however, came what the then-chairman of the Council, actor Jean-Louis Roux, called "the beginnings of a new period of growth." In October 1997, the Canadian Heritage Minister announced another $25 million of funding for 1997–98 and for each of the following 4 years.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] An additional $10-million increase in the appropriation was announced in the federal budget of February 2000.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In May 2001, further $25 million was provided to the Council by the federal government between 2001–02 and 2003–05.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2006, the Canadian government provided one-time funding of $50 million (divided into $20 million for 2006–07 and $30 million for 2007–08), all of which would go towards grants.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2007, the government announced an additional $30 million to be added permanently to the Council's base budget, bringing the Parliamentary appropriation to around $180 million in 2008–09.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council for the Arts oversees the **Art Bank** (French: *Banque d'art*), a division of the Canada Council with the mandate to rent works of art to public and private sector offices.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Art Bank's collection—the largest collection of contemporary Canadian art in the world—includes some 18,000 artworks by over 3,000 Canadian artists, including those from Indigenous backgrounds.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] These works include the 6,400 currently being rented to over 200 government and corporate clients.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] It offers public access to this art through its 3 programs: art rental, loans to museums, and outreach projects.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Established in the 1970s and developed by Canada Council Visual Arts Officer Suzanne Rivard-Lemoyne, the Art Bank buys art from notable Canadian artists through a system of peer-review juries.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Bank is completely self-funded, earning its money from renting out works in its collection, and continues to expand its collection by buying works in accord with its annual purchasing budget.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The vast majority of its art is rented by the federal government, with less than 10% being rented to the private sector.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Works of art are rented out for two-year periods.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The rental rate is generally 20% of the piece's market value.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Although located in Ottawa, Ontario, the Art Bank services its clients across the country.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Its collection has been appraised to be worth over 71 million dollars.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2002 the Canada Council Art Bank began to purchase Indigenous art to enhance its collection as part of its 45th anniversary.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Overseeing UNESCO activities in Canada, the Canada Council operates the Canadian Commission for UNESCO (CCUNESCO), which helps governments, organizations, and individual Canadians share information, along with making recommendations to the federal Canadian government on UNESCO programs and budgets.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Established by the Canada Council for the Arts in 1957, the Commission is managed by a 17-member executive committee consisting of representatives of government departments, academics, and other experts in education, culture, and world heritage.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council for the Arts promotes public awareness of the arts through its communications, research and arts promotion activities.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In particular, every year, the Canada Council awards a broad range of prizes to over 200 Canadian artists and scholars in recognition of their work.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Canada Council administers various Governor General's Awards, including Medals in Architecture, Literary Awards, Performing Arts Awards, and Awards in Visual and Media Arts.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Other awards include the Killam Program of scholarly awards, J.B.C Watkins Awards, the John G.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Diefenbaker Award, the Musical Instrument Bank, and the Walter Carsen Prize for Excellence in the Performing Arts, among others.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Diefenbaker Award**, with a prize of up to $95,000, allows a distinguished German scholar in the humanities to conduct research in Canada and spend brief periods gaining additional experience at American institutions.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Award was created in 1991, in memory of former Prime Minister John G.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Diefenbaker, as the Canadian counterpart to the Konrad Adenauer Award, which was established by the Government of Germany for Canadian scholars in 1988.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] This award is one of the most distinguished research fellowships in Canada, and was established by the Killam Trusts through Dorothy J.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Killam, in memory of her husband, Izaak Walton Killam.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The MIB was established in 1985 with a $100,000 bequest from the Barwick Family along with the fundraising efforts of businessman William Turner and cellist Denis Brott, both of Montréal.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Since then, the Bank has received donations and loans of violins, cellos, and bows—created by such luthiers as Stradivari, Gagliano, Guarneri, and Pressenda—as well as generous bequests for the Canada Council to purchase additional instruments.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Musical Instrument Bank has supported various notable Canadian classical musicians, including Lara St.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] John, Alexandre Da Costa, Martin Beaver, Judy Kang, and Denise Djokic. among others.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2018–19, the Canada Council awarded grants to over 2,800 Canadian artists, almost 450 groups, and over 2,000 arts organizations.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Each year the organization receives some 16,000 grant requests, which are reviewed by peer assessment committees.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2006–07, the Canada Council awarded some 6,000 grants to artists and arts organizations and made payments to more than 15,400 authors through the Public Lending Right Commission.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Grants and payments totaled more than $152 million.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Through its Public Lending Right (PLR) program, the Canada Council financially compensates over 17,000 Canadian authors annually for providing free public access to their books in Canadian public libraries.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Authors are compensated through direct payments ranging from CA$50 to $4,500 a year.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Eligible work includes original writing, translation, illustration, narration and photography contained in library books across a range.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The **Public Lending Right Commission** is a permanent advisory board that works with the Canada Council "to define the program's criteria and promote the program among eligible authors, illustrators, narrators and translators" from a variety of literary and scholarly genres.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Commission consists of writers, translators, librarians, and publishers, as well as non-voting representatives from the Canada Council, the Department of Canadian Heritage, Library and Archives Canada, and Bibliothèque et Archives nationales du Québec.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Author Mélikah Abdelmoumen is the current Commission Chair, with writer Russell Wangersky as Vice-Chair.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The creation of a PLR program was first deliberated in 1977, when the Council sets up the Payment for Public Use Committee to discuss the matter.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Also that year, UNEQ (Union des écrivaines et des écrivains québécois) is founded in order to defend the rights of Quebec authors.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 1982, the Applebaum-Hébert Committee recommended that the federal government create a program to pay authors for the use of their books in libraries.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Soon after, in March 1986, the **Payment for Public Use** (PPU) program was established by a Cabinet decision, with an initial budget of $3 million allocated to it by the Treasury Board Secretariat.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The initial name was promptly changed to Public Lending Right and catalogue-based system was adopted.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The PLR Commission developed and approved its Constitution and Bylaws in 1988, its second year of operation.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2008, the Commission would unanimously adopt a growth management strategy, including a new four-tier payment scale for PLR payments, which was implemented two years later.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The Commission first moved in favour of the possibility of ebooks being eligible in the PLR Program in 2011.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] However, it would not be until 2016, when the Program opened registration to ebooks.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] Also in 2016, the Program would begin to consider the future eligibility of audiobook materials, and the Canada Council would pledge to increase direct payments to authors through the PLR Program.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] In 2012, author Roy MacSkimming published the first of three major research studies related to PLR; subsequent reports would address the arrival of new technologies and compare the Canadian model to other PLR systems operating around the world.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] The PLR Program would finally open registration to audiobooks in 2019.
[src:cinema-politica/canada-council-for-the-arts] For the first time, works must have been published during the previous 5 years in order to be eligible for registration.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] Cinema Politica started in Montreal at Concordia University in 2003 as an incorporated non-profit network and organization with several chapters throughout Canada and abroad.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] Cinema Politica is funded through arts council grants, membership fees, distribution revenues and audience donations.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] Most CP locals are based on campuses in Canada and Europe, but the organization has locations off-campus (community locals) and in other parts of the world including Latin America and Africa.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] Cinema Politica states that its mandate is to support "alternative, independent, and radical political film and video, and the artists who dare to devote time, passion and resources to telling stories from the margins.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] CP is mainly funded by the Canada Council for the Arts, membership fees from locals, fundraising and donations from audience members.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] CP has partnerships with the following distributors: the National Film Board of Canada, Mongrel Media, Women Make Movies, les Films du 3 mars, Java Films, and others.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] Each year Cinema Politica nominates the 10 most-screened films in the network for the CP Audience Award.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] Audiences members across the network choose the winner.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] This award is presented to a Canadian filmmaker who "has shown a commitment to community and resistance in documentary filmmaking." The award is named after the prolific National Film Board director Alanis Obomsawin.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] The first Alanis Award was given to John Greyson in March 2011.
[src:cinema-politica/cinema-politica] Cinema Politica is governed by a board of directors, and is aided in their work by the members of an advisory committee.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia is a non-sectarian and coeducational institution, with more than 270,000 alumni.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university's varsity teams, known as the Stingers, compete in the Quebec Student Sport Federation of U Sports.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The roots of Concordia University's founding institutions go back more than 120 years with the establishment of Loyola College in 1896 and Sir George Williams University in 1926.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Loyola College traces its history to an English-language program at the Collège Sainte-Marie de Montréal (today part of the Université du Québec à Montréal) at the Jesuit Sacred Heart Convent.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1896, Loyola College was established at the corner of Bleury Street and Saint Catherine Street, and it was named in honour of Ignatius of Loyola, founder of the Society of Jesus.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] On March 10, 1898, the institution was incorporated by the Government of Quebec and became a full-fledged college.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The same year, following a fire, the college was relocated further west on Drummond Street, south of Saint Catherine Street.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Although founded as a *collège classique* (the forerunners of Quebec's college system), Loyola began granting university degrees through Université Laval in 1903.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The college moved into the present west-end campus on Sherbrooke Street West in Notre-Dame-de-Grâce in 1916.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Since Loyola College never became a chartered university, it did not have the ability to grant its own university degrees.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1920, the institution became affiliated with Université de Montréal, which began granting its degrees instead of Université Laval.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Memorial bronze honour roll plaques in the entrance hall near the administrative offices are dedicated to those from Loyola College who fought in the First World War, Second World War and Korean War.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The inter-war period was marked by the shift of education in the institution, the *collège classique* education was replaced by humanistic education (Liberal Arts College) in 1940, and Loyola became a four-year institution.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Theology and philosophy were taught to all students until 1972.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1940, the Faculty of Science and the Department of Engineering were created.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In addition to providing the same undergraduate programs as other colleges, the institution also offered innovative fields of study at the time, such as exercise science and communication studies.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Students could enrol in academic majors starting in 1953 and honours programs in 1958.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Students graduating from Loyola could afterwards pursue graduate-level education in other universities, with a few earning Rhodes Scholarships.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Starting in 1958, Loyola also began offering its first evening courses for students who were not able to go to school full-time.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] New courses were given in library science and faith community nursing.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Since its creation, Loyola College had welcomed almost exclusively young English-speaking Catholic men as students.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Obtaining a university charter was an important issue in the 1960s.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Although many wanted Loyola College to become Loyola University, the Government of Quebec preferred to annex it to Sir George Williams University.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Negotiations began in 1968 and ended with the creation of Concordia University on August 24, 1974.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1851, the first YMCA in North America was established on Ste.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Beginning in 1873, the YMCA offered evening classes to allow working people in the English-speaking community to pursue their education while working during the day.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Sixty years later, the Montreal YMCA relocated to its current location on Stanley Street in Downtown Montreal.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1926, the education program at the YMCA was reorganized as Sir George Williams College, named after George Williams, founder of the original YMCA in London, England, upon which the Montreal YMCA was based.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1934, Sir George Williams College offered the first undergraduate credit course in adult education in Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Sir George Williams College received its university charter from the provincial government in 1948, though it remained the education arm of the Montreal YMCA.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Sir George Williams expanded into its first standalone building, the Norris Building, in 1956.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1959, the college requested that the Quebec legislature amend its university charter, changing its name to Sir George Williams University.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It established a Centre for Human Relations and Community Studies in 1963.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Sir George Williams continued to hold classes in the YMCA building until the construction of the Henry F.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university gained international attention in 1969 for what is known as the "Computer Centre Incident." Notably in spring 1968, six black West Indian students at Sir George Williams University accused a biology lecturer (later assistant professor) of racism.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The complaint was lodged to the dean of students, Magnus Flynn.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Dissatisfied with how the administration was handling their complaint, the students decided to make it a public issue in fall 1968.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The students occupied and destroyed the Hall Building's ninth floor computer lab after threatening to do so should the riot squad be called.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The events forced the university to re-evaluate its policies, leading to the creation of the Ombuds Office and establishment of the University Regulations on Rights and Responsibilities in April 1971.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Following several years of discussions and planning, Sir George Williams University merged with Loyola College to create Concordia University in 1974.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia provided students with representative student organizations and greater power over administrative decisions at the university.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 1968, in the wake of the Parent Commission Report, which recommended the secularization of Quebec's educational system, the Government of Quebec asked Loyola College and Sir George Williams University to consider some form of union.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The proposed merger was discussed by the Loyola-Sir George Williams Joint Steering Committee, a committee created to analyze all forms of possible mergers of the two institutions.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It was proposed, in 1969, to create a university federation that allowed students to take courses at both campuses without paying additional fees.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] There was also mention of a shuttle bus service linking the remote facilities 7 km (4.3 mi) apart.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Criticized for the difficulties encountered by the cohesion of the various departments and faculties, this option was set aside, but not totally rejected by the Joint Steering Committee.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Joint Committee of Representatives of the Board of Trustees of Loyola College and the Board of Governors of Sir George Williams University was formed in December 1971 and in fall 1972 produced a document outlining the basis of a university with two campuses.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] While the committee considered a number of possible models, including that of a loose federation, the solution finally adopted was that of an integrated institution, Concordia University, operating under the existing charter of Sir George Williams University.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Following several revisions in November 1972, the document became the main plan of the proposed merger.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It was accepted by both institutions, which began the process of consolidating their operations.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In early 1973, the two institutions announced the merger would take place that fall.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] However, legal and administrative procedures delayed the merger for another year.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] On August 24, 1974, the Government of Quebec recognized the merger, thus creating Concordia University.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The name was taken from the motto of the city of Montreal, *Concordia salus* (meaning "well-being through harmony").
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The legal existence of Concordia dates from August 24, 1974.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The integration of the various faculties of the two institutions into a coherent whole took several years.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The five faculties of the new university were a combination of existing faculties and departments prior to the merger.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] There was a Faculty of Commerce, Faculty of Science and Faculty of Arts at Sir George Williams University.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Additionally, there was a Faculty of Arts and Science at Loyola College.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Faculty of Engineering of both institutions had previously been combined.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Faculty of Fine Arts was created in 1976.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The first phase of the combination of the Faculties of Arts and Science began in 1977 and ended in 1985.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia's Center for Zero Energy Building Studies opened in 1977.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Center focuses on research into construction of more energy efficient buildings.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Vanier Library on the Loyola Campus was enlarged, while in 1992, the library on the Sir George Williams Campus moved to the new J.W.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Norris Building was closed the same year.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] On August 24, 1992, Valery Fabrikant, a mechanical engineering professor, shot five colleagues, killing four, on the ninth floor of the Hall Building.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Fabrikant was convicted of the murders and sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university erected a memorial to the slain professors (four granite tables) in the Hall Building lobby.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Starting in 1998, the university entered a major phase of expansion to meet its growing student enrolment.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In August 2003, Concordia inaugurated the Richard J.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Renaud Science Complex on the Loyola Campus.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 2005, the university launched a major urban redevelopment project in the neighbourhood surrounding the Sir George Williams Campus, known as the Quartier Concordia.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] That same year, the Engineering, Computer Science and Visual Arts Integrated Complex opened its doors on Saint Catherine Street West between Guy Street and Mackay Street.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In September 2009, the university marked the opening of the new LEED certified building for the John Molson School of Business.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The new building hosts a wall of solar panels and is 25% more energy efficient than required under code.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In September 2015, the university held a ribbon cutting for the District 3 Innovation Center's new space on the sixth floor of Concordia's Faubourg Building.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university opened its interdisciplinary Applied Science Hub in 2020 at the Loyola campus.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university has two campuses, set approximately 7 km (4 miles) apart: Sir George Williams Campus in the downtown core of Montreal, in an area known as Quartier Concordia (around the Guy–Concordia Metro station), and Loyola Campus in the residential west-end district of Notre-Dame-de-Grâce.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] They are connected by free shuttle-bus service for students, faculty and staff.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia University has three main library locations.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Howard Webster Library is located in the J.W.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] McConnell Building on the Sir George Williams Campus and the Georges P.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Vanier Library is located on the Loyola Campus.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] On September 2, 2014, the Library opened the Grey Nuns Reading Room, a silent study space for Concordia students located in the former Chapel of the Invention of the Holy Cross.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Concordia Library houses several special and unique collections including the Azrieli Holocaust Collection and the Irving Layton Collection.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Most special collections are located in the Vanier Library.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Library also maintains the university's institutional repository, Spectrum.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Library is a member of the Canadian Association of Research Libraries.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Library also has partnerships with the Canadian Research Knowledge Network and the Data Liberation Initiative.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Hall Building houses the Leonard and Bina Ellen Art Gallery.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Samuel Schecter, an art enthusiast and businessman, set up two funds in 1962 to be used for the purchase of Canadian art at Sir George Williams University and at Loyola College (Montreal).
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] When Sir George Williams University and Loyola College merged to form Concordia in 1974, their respective art collections were also combined.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The collection of the Leonard and Bina Ellen Gallery consists of 1,800 paintings, sculptures, prints, photographs and videos, many of the works by 20th-century Canadian artists.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia's Engineering, Computer Science and Visual Arts Complex houses the FOFA Gallery, a primary venue for exhibiting works by faculty, students and alumni of the Faculty of Fine Arts.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia's Visual Arts Building on René Lévesque Boulevard houses the VAV Gallery, a student-run exhibition space seeking to highlight the work of undergraduate students in the Fine Arts department.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia's Records Management and Archives stores official records of, or relating to, or people/activities connected with Concordia University and its two founding institutions.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The collection consists of manuscripts, texts, photographs, audio-visual material and artifacts.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 2001, Concordia embarked on a mission to develop and expand the quality of the downtown campus, and to revive the west end in Montreal.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university also acquired the historic Grey Nuns Mother House near its Sir George Williams Campus, for $18 million.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Built in 1871, it would alone double the size of the current downtown campus.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] From 2007 to 2022, the university moved into the building in four separate phases.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia Residence Life currently houses nearly 250 students each year in the Grey Nuns Building.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The dorm rooms are among the largest in the country, as many of the rooms have been transformed from when the section of the Grey Nuns Building was occupied by the Grey Nuns.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The site was designated a National Historic Site of Canada in 2011.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Engineering, Computer Science and Visual Arts Integrated Complex (EV Building) at Saint Catherine Street and Guy Street was opened in September 2005.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The building is directly connected to the Guy–Concordia Metro station and also houses Le Gym, a facility of Concordia's Department of Recreation and Athletics.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Across the street, the 100-year-old TD Canada Trust building was donated to Concordia in 2005 by the Toronto-Dominion Bank.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Construction of the new John Molson Building (MB), the home of the John Molson School of Business located on the corner of Guy Street and De Maisonneuve Boulevard West, began in February 2007.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] At a ceremony at Concordia on October 30, 2006, the Quebec Minister of Education, Recreation and Sports, Jean-Marc Fournier, announced an investment of $60 million towards the construction of the new building.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The government's $60 million represented about half of the total construction costs.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Construction started on January 22, 2006, and the building was completed and opened in September 2009.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The 15-story building now houses the John Molson School's about 9,100 full- and part-time students under the same roof for the first time.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The departments of contemporary dance, theatre and music also moved into the new MB Building.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It is connected to the EV Building by a tunnel under Guy Street.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In April 2010, a 120-metre tunnel completed the underground connections of the Guy-Concordia Metro station with the Henry F.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia opened the Applied Science Hub on the Loyola Campus in December 2020.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Quartier Concordia is a neighbourhood redevelopment project centred around Concordia University's Sir George Williams Campus in downtown Montreal.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] As part of the redesign, the small Norman Bethune Square was redesigned and enlarged.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Sidewalks in the area were also widened, with additional trees.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Since 2010, a tunnel links the university's Henry F.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] McConnell buildings with the Guy-Concordia Metro station.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] However, a project to create a green space on Mackay Street was put on hold.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university's long-term sustainability vision, goals and strategies have been consolidated into the Sustainability Action Plan.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] A first iteration of the Sustainability Action Plan was implemented starting in 2020 around five streams: food, waste, climate, research and curriculum.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] As part of the climate stream, the university has committed to achieving carbon neutrality by 2040.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Efforts toward this goal include its PLAN/NET ZERO initiative, where the university is using its campuses and buildings as living labs for transitioning to renewable energy and testing new technologies to reduce its energy consumption and greenhouse-gas emissions.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia is led by its president and vice-chancellor (referred to as the president), provost and vice-presidents.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Board of Governors and the Senate manage the university's affairs and academic integrity.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The president and the senior leadership ensure transparency and accountability of the administration.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The administration is supervised by the Board of Governors and Senate.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Under the Charter of Concordia University, the university's highest governing body is the Board of Governors, which has final authority over the affairs of the university.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Senate derives its authority from the Board of Governors.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university has four faculties — Faculty of Arts and Science, Faculty of Fine Arts, Gina Cody School of Engineering and Computer Science and John Molson School of Business — as well as the School of Graduate Studies.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 2021, Concordia's Board of Governors approved the creation of the School of Health, an interdisciplinary unit that serves as a hub for the university's health-related research, education and community engagement.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The respective faculties supervise the academic departments/institutes.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] For example, the Faculty of Art and Science oversees the Department of Applied Human Sciences and Simone de Beauvoir Institute.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 2024–2025, Concordia received $643.9 million in operating revenue.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Fifty-two per cent of the university's revenue comes from grants by the Government of Quebec, which are given based on the student population.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] As of 2024-2025, the university's foundation had $426.8 million in its endowment.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In November 2017, Concordia launched the Campaign for Concordia.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The campaign's original target was $250 million, since raised to $350 million.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Its goal is to support the university's nine strategic directions that will advance Concordia's position as "Canada's next-generation university." In September 2025, the university closed its campaign by announcing it had surpassed its goal and raised $365 million.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Students begin their university studies in September or, in some cases, in January or May.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] An undergraduate degree normally requires three or four years of full-time study, a master's one to three years, and a PhD at least four years.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Diplomas and certificates usually take no longer than a year and a half to complete.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia has more than 400 undergraduate programs under the Faculty of Arts and Science, the Gina Cody School of Engineering and Computer Science, the Faculty of Fine Arts and the John Molson School of Business.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Students are normally enrolled in one of these faculties but may take courses from any of the others as part of their studies.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Class sizes vary from 30 to 400 students.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The School of Graduate Studies offers about 120 programs leading to master's and doctoral degrees, and graduate diplomas and certificates for professionals seeking to upgrade their knowledge and skills.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia Continuing Education offers university-level studies and training to those from diverse backgrounds and stages of life.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Institute for Co-operative Education administers more than 70 bachelor's and master's programs in an alternating co-op work-study format.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia's co-op programs enable students to enrich their learning by participating in career-relevant 12–17-week full-time, paid work terms.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Depending on their faculty and major, co-op students will usually graduate with a minimum of 12 months of academically relevant work experience.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] There are also Industrial Experience and Professional Experience options in certain disciplines that enable students to participate in a summer-only work term.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia is a member of the Canadian Association for Co-operative Education (CAFCE).
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] During the 2024–2025 academic year, there were 35,577 undergraduate students, 8,345 graduate students and 4,735 continuing education students enrolled at Concordia.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia's Faculty of Arts and Science consists of 21 departments and seven colleges, schools and institutes in the humanities, sciences and social sciences at the undergraduate and graduate levels.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] There are 257 programs, offering more than 2,400 courses.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] There are 869 full-time and part-time faculty members.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] During the 2022–23 academic year, there were 18,502 undergraduate and graduate students enrolled in the faculty.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In addition to regular academic programs, the Faculty of Arts and Science also includes three colleges, two schools and two institutes.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] These are the Liberal Arts College, the Loyola College for Diversity and Sustainability, the School of Community and Public Affairs, the School of Irish Studies, the Science College, the Simone de Beauvoir Institute and the Concordia Institute for Canadian Jewish Studies.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Loyola College for Diversity and Sustainability (formerly Loyola International College) is an interdisciplinary college on the Loyola Campus, the original site of Loyola College.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It offers minor programs in Diversity and the Contemporary World and Sustainability Studies.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] At the undergraduate level, the Faculty of Arts and Science offers both Bachelor of Arts (BA) and Bachelor of Science (BSc) programs with majors ranging from economics, political science and sociology to actuarial mathematics, biology and ecology.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Gina Cody School of Engineering and Computer Science, formerly known as Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science, is named after Concordia alumna Gina Cody, who donated $15 million to the university in 2018.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In response, the university renamed its faculty of engineering and computer science in her honour, making it the first engineering school to be named after a woman in Canada and globally.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 2018, *Maclean's* ranked its programs as one of the best in Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The engineering programs are all accredited by the Canadian Engineering Accreditation Board (CEAB).
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] During the 2022–23 academic year, there were 11,848 undergraduate and graduate students enrolled in the faculty.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Troitsky Bridge Building Competition brings together engineering students from across Canada and parts of the United States.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Teams of students representing their universities must build a 1-metre-long bridge using only regular popsicle sticks, toothpicks, dental floss, and white glue.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] A panel of judges grades the bridges based on originality and presentation while a hydraulic loading device is used to determine the maximum load and performance.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Faculty of Fine Arts offers 26 undergraduate programs and 17 graduate programs.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It includes nine departments and four research institutes.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] During the 2022–23 academic year, there were 3,982 undergraduate and graduate students enrolled in the faculty.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Among the departments is The Mel Hoppenheim School of Cinema.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It is informally identified as MHSoC, and offers study in the fields of film animation, film production and film studies.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It is the largest, university-based centre for the study of film animation, film production and film studies in Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 221 the Indigenous Future Research Center (IFRC) was established and directed by Jason Edward Lewis.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The John Molson School of Business (formerly the Faculty of Commerce and Administration) offers 18 different programs at the undergraduate and graduate levels from five different departments.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The departments are Accountancy, Finance, Marketing, Management and Supply Chain and Business Technology Management.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] During the 2022–23 academic year there were 9,097 undergraduate students and graduate students enrolled, and John Molson School has 61,000 alumni.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The John Molson School is accredited by the Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business (AACSB).
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The business school is located in a LEED silver-certified building.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The 2024 *QS World University Rankings* ranked the university 387th in the world.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In the 2023 *Academic Ranking of World Universities* rankings, the university ranked between 501-600 in the world.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The 2024 *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* placed Concordia between 501–600 in the world.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] News & World Report* 2022–23 global university rankings, the university placed 653rd in the world.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university was also ranked by *Maclean's* Canadian university rankings.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In October 2023, *Maclean's* ranked Concordia 9th in Canada under its comprehensive universities category.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The university's John Molson School of Business was ranked among the top 10 Canadian business schools and the top 100 worldwide by *The Economist* in 2022.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Four residence buildings are available for students who wish to live on campus: Grey Nuns Residence, Jesuit Residence, Hingston Hall (HA) and Hingston Hall (HB).
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] For students who choose to live off campus, the Concordia Student Union's Off-Campus Housing and Job Bank (HoJo) offers classified ads, legal advice and safety resources.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia University's athletic teams are called the Concordia Stingers.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] They compete with other schools in Canadian Interuniversity Sport, and more specifically, in the Quebec Student Sports Federation and the Quebec University Football League.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In the fall, teams compete in Canadian football, men's and women's soccer, men's and women's rugby union and college wrestling.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] There are female and male wrestlers on the team from year to year, and they compete as one team.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In the winter, teams compete in men's and women's ice hockey and men's and women's basketball.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Concordia Stingers women's ice hockey team won the Canadian national championships in 1998, 1999, 2022 and 2024.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] In 2025-2026, the team won the provincial championship and finished second in the national championship.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Concordia Student Union (CSU) represents undergraduate students.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Its membership totals more than 35,000 students.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia students voted in favour of accreditation of their student union in a referendum in December 2000.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] As a result, the CSU is now legally accountable only to its student constituents.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia University is home to local and international fraternities and sororities.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia University has a campus radio station, CJLO, and a television station, CUTV.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Concordia also has two student-run newspapers, *The Link* and *The Concordian* (which includes French-language pages run by L'Organe*)*.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] *The Concordian* is a member of Canadian University Press (CUP); *The Link* left the CUP network in 2012.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The Sir George Williams affair (also referred to as "The Sir George Williams Computer Centre Incident") was a 1969 event at Sir George Williams University, now a part of Concordia University.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] It was the largest student occupation in Canadian history, and resulted (in 1969 currency) in $2 million of property damage.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Among those arrested and convicted were Roosevelt Douglas, who later became Prime Minister of Dominica, and who was a son of one of the richest men in Dominica.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Also arrested was Anne Cools, who later became a Canadian Senator.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Deeply involved also was student Cheddi "Joey" Jagan Jr., who was of Indo-Guyanese and Ashkenazi Jewish descent, and the son of Cheddi Jagan, an American-educated dentist and former Premier and Chief Minister of British Guiana at the time, and his American wife Janet Jagan.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] As the 1990s progressed, student activism began growing, coming to a head in 1999 with the election of the first in a series of radical slates to the Concordia Student Union.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Under the presidency of Rob Green, a referendum regarding a strike garnered 2,284 votes of support.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] This was an unusually strong show of support, as student governments at Concordia are often elected on the basis of less than 1,000 votes in their favour.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The strike lasted from November 3 to 5 and targeted a range of issues, including student representation in the university senate, corporate presence and advertising on campus, and government.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] There were several demonstrations, where both protesters and police were reported to be injured.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] On September 9, 2002, a scheduled speech from the former (and later subsequent) Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was cancelled following violent pro-Palestinian riots inside the Henry F.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Protestors raised concerns about Israeli human rights abuses in the Palestinian territories, namely in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] Netanyahu accused protestors of being supporters of terrorism.
[src:cinema-politica/concordia-university] The event is depicted in a documentary named *Confrontation at Concordia*.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] The documentary Dreamland addresses the question of whether Iceland should preserve its unspoiled, unique nature or whether the nation should build enormous dams to produce hydro-electric energy.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] The film shows how implementing "green energy" to provide aluminum industries with cheap energy threatens the natural wonders of Iceland.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] Through interviews with economists, psychologists, historians, poets, editors, and industry managers, the film delivers insight into different point of views.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] The documentary illustrates the fact that fear is a powerful emotion and a way of controlling people.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] For example, the fear of unemployment often leads to a limited view of other possible alternatives.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] To develop the countryside of Iceland and to employ its citizens, the Icelandic government made Iceland the biggest aluminum manufacturer.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] The second theme of the documentary is how the economy benefits from war.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] The American military base in Keflavík increased the economy of Iceland, but when the United States no longer needed the base, Icelanders feared for their jobs, and the Icelandic government desperately lobbied the American military to stay.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] The documentary streams pictures of a beautiful, untouched nature, including volcanoes, glaciers, mountains, and waterfalls, followed by gigantic hydro towers and dams that destroy the wilderness and beautiful landscape.
[src:cinema-politica/dreamland-2009-film] It makes use of clips from the 2005 documentary *Wira Pdika*, about Bauxite mining in the Niyamgiri hills of Odisha, to emphasise the relationship of aluminium smelting in Iceland to exploitation elsewhere.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson has won accolades and achieved critical success with his films—most notably *Zero Patience* (1993) and *Lilies* (1996).
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] His outspoken persona, activism, and public image have also attracted international press and controversy.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson is also a professor at York University's film school, where he teaches film and video theory, film production, and editing.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson was born in Nelson, British Columbia, the son of Dorothy F.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] He was raised in London, Ontario, before moving to Toronto in 1978, where he became a writer for *The Body Politic* and other local arts and culture magazines, as well as a video and performance artist.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] He directed several short films, including *The Perils of Pedagogy*, *Kipling Meets the Cowboy*, and *Moscow Does Not Believe in Queers*, before releasing his first feature film, *Pissoir*, in 1988.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] *Pissoir* is a response to the homophobic climate of the period and, particularly, to police entrapment of men in public washrooms (toilets) and parks and police raids on gay bathhouses.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson’s early video work was “social change documentary.” During the 1980s and 1990s, Greyson created many videos as a form of AIDS activism.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] One of his first videos to address AIDS was *Moscow Does Not Believe in Queers* (1986).
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson's next film was *The Making of Monsters*, a short musical film produced during Greyson's residency at the Canadian Film Centre in 1991.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film deals with the 1985 murder by five adolescent males of Kenneth Zeller, a high school teacher and librarian, when he was allegedly cruising for sexual encounters in Toronto's High Park.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film is a fictional documentary about the making of a movie-of-the-week, entitled *Monsters*, in which the young murderers are depicted as psychopathic monsters, rather than normal teenage boys.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film features Marxist literary critic Georg Lukács as the producer of *Monsters*, with Bertolt Brecht (played by a catfish) as director.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson's film was pulled from distribution when the estate of Kurt Weill objected to its use of the tune of Mack the Knife.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson had originally received copyright permission to use the tune, but it was withdrawn, apparently because Weill's estate objected to the film's homosexual themes.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Although copyright is no longer an issue, having lapsed in 2000, fifty years after Weill's death, the film has not yet been re-released by the Canadian Film Development Corporation.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The copyright issues that came out of creating *The Making of Monsters* inspired documentary segments in his film *Un©ut* (1997), which explored debates around how copyright law affects artists, outing public figures (with the example of Pierre Trudeau), and circumcision.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] He is best known for the feature-length films *Zero Patience* and *Lilies*.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] He has also directed for television, including episodes of *Queer as Folk*, *Made in Canada*, and *Paradise Falls*.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In 2003, Greyson and composer David Wall created *Fig Trees*, a video opera for gallery installation, about the struggles of South African AIDS activist Zackie Achmat.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In 2009, a film version of *Fig Trees* was released.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] This film, a feature-length documentary opera, premiered at the Berlinale as part of its Panorama section, where it won the Teddy Award for Best Documentary.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In 2007, Greyson was the recipient of the Bell Award in Video Art.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The award committee stated: "John Greyson is perhaps best known to a general public as a feature film director.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] He shoots his 'film' projects on video with trademark video post-production techniques, thus colonizing the space of cinema with the aesthetics of video.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] An incisive social and political critic, Mr.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson is in fact one of the leaders in the AIDS activist video movement, among others.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In 2020, he released the short film *Prurient* as part of the *Greetings from Isolation* project.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In 2021, his experimental short *International Dawn Chorus Day* had its world premiere at the Berlin International Film Festival, where it won the Teddy Award for best LGBTQ-themed short film.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In 2022, Greyson’s eighth feature, *Photo Booth*, had its world premiere at the 15th Toronto Palestine Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film follows two Palestinian queer activists, who, along with novelist Jean Genet, attempt to sabotage the Eurovision Song Contest, being held in Jericho.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film was billed as “a split-screen documentary opera,” and included interviews from Ghadir Shafie, Judith Butler, and Ali Abunimah, among others.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson’s film *Door Prize* (2024) had its world premiere at the 2025 Images Festival in Toronto, Ontario.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film is about a trans bike courier, named Mars, who is killed by an SUV, and the true crime spectacle that follows his death.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] A number of sub-plots centre around specific criticisms of the social response to AIDS by politicians, doctors and pharmaceutical companies.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The central scene in *Zero Patience*, however, is probably the scene in which Zero looks through a microscope at a slide of his own blood.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] What he sees is the subject of an Esther Williams-like song-and-dance number throughout which Zero converses with Miss HIV (Michael Callen).
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In 1996, Greyson released his most famous film, *Lilies*, an adaptation of Michel Marc Bouchard's play *Les feluettes, ou un drame romantique*.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film screened at numerous festivals, including Sundance, and received critical acclaim; it was nominated for 14 awards Genie Awards at the 17th ceremony, winning four, including Best Picture.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film also won a number of other awards, including the GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Film.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Following the dual chronology of Bouchard's play, Greyson's film (for which Bouchard wrote the screenplay) moves between two time periods: the film's 'present' in 1952 and the events that took place in the town of Roberval, Quebec in 1912.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The film begins with a visit by Bishop Bilodeau (Marcel Sabourin) to a prison chapel where he is supposed to hear the confession of convicted murderer Simon (Aubert Pallascio).
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Both men were at school together in 1912 when a fire supposedly set by Simon took the life of a third schoolmate, and Simon's lover, Vallier (Danny Gilmore).
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] However, this apparently simple story become quickly more complicated when the prison chaplain (Ian D.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Clark) and the prisoners lock Bilodeau into the confessional booth and proceed to stage the true story of Vallier's death before their captive's eyes.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The feature film *Fig Trees* (2009) has been the recipient of a number of awards, including the Teddy for Best Documentary at the Berlinale, and the Best Canadian Feature award at the Toronto Inside Out Film Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In September 2009, Greyson withdrew his short documentary, *Covered*, from the Toronto International Film Festival (TIFF) festival to protest the festival's inaugural City to City Spotlight on the city of Tel Aviv.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson also argued that "my protest isn't against the films of filmmakers you've chosen... [but] is against the Spotlight itself" and the failure of the festival to include Palestinian voices.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Chilean wines in 1973 ... or South African fruit in 1991".
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson's stance and the proceeding *Toronto Declaration* immediately triggered international debate.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson's actions drew criticism from a number of sources.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Cameron Bailey, one of the festival's co-directors, stated that "The City to City series was conceived and curated entirely independently.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] There was no pressure from any outside source.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Contrary to rumours or mistaken media reports, this focus is a product only of TIFF's programming decisions.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] We value that independence and would never compromise it." Bailey also argued that "[Mr.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson] writes that his protest isn't against the films or filmmakers we have chosen, but against the spotlight itself.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Columnist George Jonas, writing in the *National Post*, argued that Greyson was engaging in "mental gymnastics," and described Greyson's line of reasoning as follows: "Who, us, objecting to Israeli films?
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] We're only objecting to Israeli propaganda.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Well, the Israeli films we're objecting to." Jonas also asked rhetorically "What Israeli film wouldn't be Israeli propaganda for Greyson?" Jonas also argued "To hear [Greyson] object to "state-subsidized propaganda" is ironic, to say the least.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson later posted a response to Lantos that was published in Rabble.ca.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Patrick Goldstein, a film critic and columnist for the *Los Angeles Times* wrote that he thinks "it's especially unhealthy to ... accuse a festival of being a propaganda vehicle, as the Toronto protesters have, just because it is promoting another country's film culture.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] A number of Hollywood celebrities circulated a letter on September 15, 2009, protesting a petition calling for a boycott of the Toronto International Film Festival over a Tel Aviv-themed event.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The letter, which appeared simultaneously in the *Los Angeles Times* and the *Toronto Star* was signed, among others, by Jerry Seinfeld, Sacha Baron Cohen, Natalie Portman, Jason Alexander, Lisa Kudrow, Lenny Kravitz, Patricia Heaton, Jacob Richler, Noah Richler, George F.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] A letter for support for Greyson, termed the *Toronto Declaration*, was signed by more than 50 people, including Israeli filmmaker Udi Aloni, director Ken Loach, musician David Byrne, actors Danny Glover and Jane Fonda, author Alice Walker and journalist Naomi Klein.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Jane Fonda would later reconsider her position and released a publicity statement on the matter.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] "I signed the letter without reading it carefully enough, without asking myself if some of the wording wouldn't exacerbate the situation rather than bring about constructive dialogue," Fonda wrote on the Huffington Post website.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] She added that the suffering of both sides should be articulated.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In summer 2011, Greyson traveled to Greece to participate in the Freedom Flotilla II, specifically joining with the "Tahrir," the Canadian member of the Flotilla.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] In the summer of 2013, Greyson traveled to Egypt, where he and Dr.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Tarek Loubani, a 33-year-old emergency room doctor from London, Ontario, were detained without charges, in a cell with 38 other people.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Reports indicate the two were on their way to Gaza to carry out medical relief work, but were forced to remain in Cairo as the crossing was closed.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] They remained in detention from August 16 to October 5, 2013.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson's union, the York University Faculty Association, ran a campaign via LabourStart in an effort to force the Egyptian government to release him.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] Greyson and Loubani began a hunger strike on September 16 to protest their treatment.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The Canadian government announced on October 5 that Greyson and Loubani had been released, however they were unable to board a flight to Frankfurt due to remaining on a no-fly list issued by government prosecutors.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] On October 10, Greyson and Loubani were cleared for departure and left Egypt for home the next day.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] His partner is Canadian visual artist Stephen Andrews, with whom he has lived since the 1990s.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] They have been referred to as a "power couple" in Canada's art scene.
[src:cinema-politica/john-greyson] The Art Gallery of Ontario recently installed a retrospective of Andrews' work exploring AIDS, surveillance, war, memory and chaos theory.
[src:cinema-politica/mongrel-media] In 2021, the company launched its own proprietary streaming service, offering a selection of films from both its catalogue and that of the American Magnolia Pictures library available from its website for a subscription fee of $6.99 per month.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The **National Film Board of Canada** (**NFB**; French: *Office national du film du Canada, ONF*) is a Canadian public film and digital media producer and distributor.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] An agency of the Government of Canada, the NFB produces and distributes documentary films, animation, web documentaries, and alternative dramas.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In total, the NFB has produced over 43,000 productions since its inception, which have won over 5,000 awards.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB reports to the Parliament of Canada through the Minister of Canadian Heritage.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] It has bilingual production programs and branches in English and French, including multicultural-related documentaries.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Exhibits and Publicity Bureau was founded on 19 September 1918, and was reorganized into the Canadian Government Motion Picture Bureau in 1923.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The organization's budget stagnated and declined during the Great Depression.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Frank Badgley, who served as the bureau's director from 1927 to 1941, stated that the bureau needed to transition to sound films or else it would lose its access to theatrical releases, but the organization did not gain the equipment until 1934, and by then it had lost its theatrical distributors.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Badgley was able to get a 16 mm film facility for the bureau in 1931.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The bureau was reorganized into the National Film Board of Canada on 11 June 1941, following John Grierson's recommendation.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Ross McLean was working as the secretary to High Commissioner Vincent Massey when he met Grierson, and asked for Grierson to come to Canada to aide in the governmental film policy.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson made a report on the Canadian film industry in 1938, and the *National Film Act*, which he drafted, was passed on 2 May 1939 causing the creation of the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The position of Film Commissioner was left vacant for months, as Ned Corbett declined the appointment, until Grierson, who proposed Badgley and Walter Turnbull for the position, accepted the position for six months in October 1939, but served until 1945.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson selected McLean to work as assistant commissioner and Stuart Legg to oversee the productions.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson sent in a letter of resignation on 27 November 1940, in protest of the CGMPB and NFB not being merged, but agreed to stay on for another six months and the merger happened.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Employment rose from 55 to 787 from 1941 to 1945, although it was cut by 40% after the war ended.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson made efforts to increase the theatrical distribution of NFB films, primarily its war-related films, as he was coordinating wartime information for the United Kingdom in North America.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Famous Players aided in distribution and the Canadian Motion Picture War Services Committee, which worked with the War Activities Committee of the Motion Pictures Industry, was founded in 1940.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] NFB productions such as *The World in Action* was watched by 30-40 million people per month in the United Kingdom and United States in 1943, and *Canada Carries On* was watched by 2.25 million people by 1944.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The audience for NFB newsreels reached 40-50 million per week by 1944.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1942, the NFB and the Wartime Information Board organized 30 film circuits that would bring NFB films to 20 rural areas once a month.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] By 1945, this number grew to 92 circuits with an attendance of 2,220 per circuit.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson opposed feature film production as he believed that Canada did not have a large enough market for an independent feature film industry.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] He supported working with American film companies and stated that "the theatre film business is an international business, dependent when it comes to distribution on an alliance or understanding with American film interests".
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] He travelled to Hollywood in 1944, and the NFB sent scripts to American companies for consideration.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] With 800 employees in 1945, the NFB was one of the largest film studios in the world.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson lacked strong support in the Canadian government and some of his films received opposition from members of the government.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] *Inside Fighting Russia* was criticized for its support of the Russian Revolution and *Balkan Powderkeg* for criticizing the United Kingdom's policy in the Balkans.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson and the NFB were attacked during the onset of the Cold War.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Federal Bureau of Investigation created a file on Grierson in 1942, due to the *World in Action* newsreel being considered too left-wing.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Leo Dolan, an ally of Hepburn and the head of the Canadian Government Travel Bureau, accused Grierson of being Jewish and a Co-operative Commonwealth Federation supporter.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Gouzenko Affair implicated Freda Linton, one of Grierson's secretaries, and the organization was criticized by the Progressive Conservative Party for subversive tendencies, financial waste, and being a monopoly.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson was also accused of being involved, but was proven not to be.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] During McLean's tenure film production was divided into four units in 1948.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Unit A dealt with agriculture, non-English, and interpretative films, Unit B dealt with sponsored, scientific, cultural, and animated films, Unit C dealt with theatrical, newsreels, tourist, and travel films, and Unit D dealt with international affairs and special projects.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] This system continued until its abolition on 28 February 1964 when it had seven units, five English-language and two French-language.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1947, Grant McLean, the cousin of the NFB commissioner, shot *The People Between* and the Secretary of State for External Affairs's department stated that some parts of the film were too favorable towards the Chinese Communist Party.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Quebec Premier Maurice Duplessis had NFB films removed from schools using accusations of communism.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Royal Canadian Mounted Police discovered that an employee for the NFB's Production Division, who was a communist, took photos of top-secret military equipment.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Department of National Defence prohibited the NFB from making films for it.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Ross McLean followed the recommendations of the department and declared the NFB a vulnerable agency and the RCMP requested the firing of 36 employees.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The RCMP requested him to fire a list of employees, McLean refused to fire any employees without their disloyalty being proven.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] He was not reappointed as commissioner and replaced by William Arthur Irwin in 1950.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Irwin reduced the demand and only three were fired.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Vincent Paquette became the NFB's first French-Canadian filmmaker in 1941, and directed *La Cité de Notre-Dame*, the board's first in-house French-language film, in 1942.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The number of French-Canadian employees grew to seventeen by 1945, and a quarter of the board's budget was spent on French productions.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Seventy English films were released by the board in 1949, while four French films were released.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Massey Commission and Gratien Gélinas, a member of the NFB's Board of Governors, called for an improvement in French-language productions, but Duplessis opposed it.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Irwin, the editor of *Maclean's*, was selected to replace McLean as commissioner of the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Film production was centralized under Irwin by having one person oversee the four film units.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] He selected Donald Mulholland over James Beveridge and Mulholland was criticized for ignoring French-language film production.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Unit E, dealing with sponsored work, and Unit F, dealing with French-language films, were created in 1951.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Royal Commission on National Development in the Arts, Letters and Sciences, with Massey as its chair, was formed in 1949.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB submitted a brief asking to have a headquarters constructed, budget increases, and to become a Crown corporation.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Robert Winters, whose ministry oversaw the NFB, stated that its brief did not represent government policy.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The commission's report supported the NFB and its requests for Crown corporation status and a headquarters were accepted.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1950, Irwin wrote to Robert Winters about a report on restructuring the NFB and Winters told Irwin to rewrite the 1939 *Film Act* as it was outdated by then.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The *National Film Act* was passed in June, and took effect on 14 October.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] A Canadian tour by Princess Elizabeth and Prince Philip was filmed using 35 mm Eastman colour-film stock, which was not available to the public yet.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The film was initially meant to be two reels, worth twenty minutes, but grew to five reels as they could not determine what to cut.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Irwin met with Harvey Harnick, the NFB's Columbia theatrical distributor, and J.J.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Fitzgibbons, the president of Famous Players, and Fitzgibbons told Irwin that he would screen all five reels if the film was completed for a Christmas release.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] *Royal Journey* opened in seventeen first-run theatres and over course of the next two years it was screened in 1,249 Canadian theatres where it was watched by a record two million people and the film was also screened in forty other countries.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The film cost $88,000, but the NFB gained a profit of $150,000 and the film's success was one of the reasons Grierson stated that Irwin "saved the Film Board".
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB created its first television series, *Window on Canada* and *On the Spot*, with the CBC in 1953.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, the CBC opposed increasing the amount of NFB productions as they believed it was hurting CBC's growth.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The majority of the filmmakers in the NFB opposed moving into television.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Sydney Newman and Gordon Burwash, who supported moving into television, were sent to the United States in 1948 to learn about TV production and NBC was given the right to air NBC productions in exchange.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] When Newman and Burwash returned, they joined the CBC as the NFB was unable to move into television.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Half of all productions by the NFB were made to air on television by 1955.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1956, the CBC's exclusion grew to them making *Hawkeye and the Last of the Mohicans* with the expressed prohibition of NFB involvement and rejecting a show by the NFB based on *Jake and the Kid*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Irwin resigned as commissioner in May 1953, and later stated that he wanted to be more involved in film production, but his time was being taken up by administrative purposes.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Albert Trueman, president of the University of New Brunswick and a member of the board of governors of the NFB and CBC, was selected by Winters to replace Irwin.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] A reshuffling of the cabinet had Walter Edward Harris become the new minister responsible for the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Since the foundation of the NFB its offices were divided across multiple locations in Ottawa and plans created during World War II to construct a single headquarters were not acted upon.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Montreal was selected during Irwin's administration due to its bilingualism and two Canadian Broadcasting Corporation television stations being created there.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Laurent reached an agreement with Duplessis to allow the move.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Donald Mulholland, the director of production, ended his support for the relocation to Montreal after Irwin's resignation and argued against it.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Trueman did not take a position and instead sent the information to Harris.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Laurent was angered by this and asked Winters if Trueman was attempting to sabotage the relocation and Trueman told Winters that he was just giving Harris information about the situation.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Conservatives criticized the rising cost of the headquarters' construction and attempted to block it, but failed.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The building was constructed from 1953 to 1956, at a cost of $5.25 million and served as the NFB's headquarters until 2019.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Most of the NFB's operations and 400 employees were moved to Saint-Laurent, Quebec, from 1955 to 1956.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In September 1954, Quebec censors demanded that the NFB pay a censorship fee of $20,500 per year and Trueman wanted to accept it in order to avoid controversy.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, a compromise was reached where the Quebec censors were given one print of each film and if they censored it then all versions would be also censored while the NFB would pay an annual fee between $2,500-3,000.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Pierre Juneau, who was sent to the United Kingdom by Irwin, was brought by Trueman to the NFB as an adviser and secretary in 1953.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The creation of two assistant commissioners, one English and one French, with Juneau as the French assistant commissioner was proposed in November 1954, but was rejected by Jack Pickersgill, who replaced Harris, over the course of the next three years.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] André Laurendeau criticized the NFB for not creating a French-language side.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In February 1957, Pickersgill allowed for Juneau to become the executive director and be in charge of financial administration and distribution.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] This was criticized by *Montréal-Matin*, *Le Devoir*, *L'Action catholique*, and other French-language media and Juneau was criticized for demoting Roger Blais, who claimed it was for him criticizing the salary inequality between French and English speakers.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Trueman accepted the position of commissioner with the promise that he would later be given a more prestigious position.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] He resigned during the French media criticism to become head of the Canada Council in 1957.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] He suggested Gérard Pelletier as his successor, but Guy Roberge, a former Liberal member of the Legislative Assembly of Quebec who had written sections of the Massey report, was selected instead as the first French-Canadian commissioner.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] *Le Devoir* supported his selection and the French media ended its criticism of the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Ellen Fairclough, who became the minister responsible for the NFB in May 1958, was not interested with the organization and never saw a film created by the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] She declined to interfere in NFB matters despite criticism from Pickersgill, who believed that the minister was responsible for whatever went on at the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Upon his arrival at the NFB in 1953, Juneau saw the difficulties of communication between French and English speakers and supported creating separate English and French production units.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Additional units for French-language film production were created in 1958.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] A French-language branch of the NFB that was independent of its English-language productions was formed on 1 January 1964, under the leadership of Pierre Juneau.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] One-third of the NFB's budget was given to French-language productions.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1962, Roberge proposed the creation of an organization to aid in film finance based on the National Film Finance Corporation and Centre national du cinéma et de l'image animée.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Interdepartmental Committee on the Possible Development of a Feature Film Industry in Canada, under Roberge's leadership, was formed by the secretary of state.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The committee submitted a report to the 19th Canadian Ministry for the creation of a loan fund to aid the development of the Canadian film industry.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The proposal was approved in October 1965, and legislation, the *Canadian Film Development Corporation Act* of 1966–67, for its creation was introduced in June 1966, before being approved on 3 March 1967, establishing the Canadian Film Development Corporation.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Denys Arcand, Gilles Carle, Jacques Godbout, Gilles Groulx, and Clément Perron criticized the NFB and its productions in articles written for the *Cité Libre*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Juneau stated that the articles were a watershed moment in the NFB's history.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Many employees left the NFB following the reprimands including Michel Brault, Carle, Bernard Gosselin, Groulx, and Arthur Lamothe.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Juneau left the NFB in March 1966, and worked at the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission before becoming president of the CBC.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Roberge created the positions of Assistant Government Film Commissioner, held by Grant McLean and Roland Ladouceur, Director of Production for English, held by Julian Biggs, and French, held by Marcel Martin, productions.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Roberge resigned as commissioner on 1 April 1966, and declined to be involved with the selection of his successor.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grant was appointed as the acting commissioner by Judy LaMarsh.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] LaMarsh was slow on the selection of a permanent commissioner.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson supported Grant's selection, but also put forward Newman.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Hugo McPherson was selected to become commissioner in April 1967.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Maurice Lamontagne selected Gordon Sheppard, a film producer, to review Canada's cultural policy and his report, Sheppard's Special Report on the Cultural Policy and Activities of the Government of Canada, was critical of the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] It criticized the NFB's preference for aesthetics and cultural films instead of informational films.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The report called for a reduction in NFB productions and that it should eventually be entirely replaced by private production.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The External Affairs Ministry criticized Sheppard stating that he was serving his own interests.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] There had been multiple attempts by the NFB to create a film school and the idea received support from the External Affairs Ministry and the Sheppard Report.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, the Treasury Board of Canada had rejected efforts to fund its creation.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson was invited by Grant to report on the possibility of creating a film school.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Grierson supported creating a school, if the External Affairs Ministry recommended that production be reduced to free up creative teachers.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The CBC terminated its contracts with the NFB in 1966.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The CBC and NFB's relations soured due to the NFB's demand that no commercials be played during their films and the NFB charging $10,000–$15,000 for 30 minute films while a commercial network had received it for $800.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The CBC and NFB also co-produced *The Ernie Game* and *Waiting for Caroline* which went overbudget by $50,000 and $200,000 respectively.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1967, the Treasury Board limited the NFB's expenditures to $10 million and over the course of two years it was forced to pay for built-in higher salary costs and another salary increase due to an agreement with the SGCT union using existing funds.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] McPherson asked Pelletier to allow the NFB to spend over $500,000 more than its budget in order to avoiding firing 10% of the NFB's employees, and later asked the Cabinet and Treasury for more funding, but was unsuccessful.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] McPherson later stated that after his failure with the Treasury he waited for the perfect time to resign.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1969, an agreement was reached between the CBC and NFB in which the CBC would be allowed to air commercials during NFB programs.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Revenue from sponsored films declined from $2.2 million to $1.6 million by August 1969.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] McPherson announced that 10% of the employees would be laid off by 1 January 1970.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The employees formed a Crisis Committee under John Howe's leadership and film production was stopped although a strike was not officially called.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The committee suggested allowing government sponsors to choose between using the NFB or private companies, allowing outsiders to pay for NFB technical services, creating a unit system where 5-15 people would work together, and creating fees for distribution.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] McPherson supported the idea of distribution fees and thought that it was the only viable option for the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Pelletier approved the NFB charging $3–12 per day for its films, but they were later removed as being in violation of anti-inflation guidelines.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Treasury had granted $1 million, $250,000 less than what was requested, in August to cover NFB's salary increases, but McPherson was not informed as ministers hoped he would institute larger budget cuts.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] An additional $500,000 was free due to lowered production following the Crisis Committee's formation.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] 63 layoffs were proposed and it was reduced by 17 due to union opposition.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The first usage of videotape by the NFB occurred in 1967, when Claude Jutra and Robert Forget used it for research with children.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Newman, a former NFB director who spent the previous twelve years working on television shows in the United Kingdom, was selected to replaced McPherson as commissioner in 1970, and he selected André Lamy as his assistant commissioner.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Faulkner opposed Newman and worked to have Newman not reappointed in July 1975, and he was replaced by Lamy.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Lamy criticized multiple French productions, such as *Cotton Mill, Treadmill*, *24 heures ou plus*, and *Un pays sans bon sens!*, as being too biased or separatist and were ordered to not be released in 1970.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] French films banned under Newman's tenure were later released during Lamy's tenure.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Kathleen Shannon attempted to have a division created to focus on films made by and about women due to the coming International Women's Year.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Newman and Robert Verrall supported Shannon's attempt to get a $1.3 million budget for a women's department, but it was rejected by the Treasury.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Verrall gave Shannon permission to organize Studio D, the first publicly funded feminist film-production unit in the world, in 1974.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, there would be no French version of Studio D until the formation of Studio B in 1986.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Studio D produced 125 films before its closure in 1996.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1970, Pelletier called for the creation of a Canadian Film Commission, made up of private and governmental interests, but it was opposed by the NFB, CBC, CFDC, and Library and Archives Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, they did agree to form the Advisory Committee on Film as an ad hoc committee.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Pelletier later proposed the Global Film Policy in which the NFB would regionalize and share sponsored productions with the private sector.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Pelletier's successor, Hugh Faulkner, replaced the Global Film Policy with the Capital Cost Allowance in which investors could get a 100% tax deduction.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Faulkner proposed to shift the responsibility of sponsored films to the Department of Supply and Services and only give the NFB 30% of the work.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, he was replaced by John Roberts during a shuffling of the cabinet in September 1976.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Roberts believed that the CCA resolved the funding problems for the private industry, accepted Lamy's recommendations for interactions with private companies, and declined to have the Department of Supply and Services manage sponsored films.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, 70% of the sponsored work were given to private companies by the end of Lamy's tenure.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] A $500,000 budget cut and 2.5% decrease in salaries over two years were implemented in 1975, after initially being threatened with a $1 million cut, as part of a government attempt to save $1 billion.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Public Service Staff Relations Board ruled in 1977 that 99% of the freelance workers at the NFB were employees and the board of governors later recommended the firing of sixty-five people.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Federal budget cuts caused Roberts to plan for the NFB's budget to decrease by 10% between 1979 and 1981.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Lamy left the NFB and the board of Governors selected James de Beaujeu Domville, who served as deputy film commissioner for seven years, after four months.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Macerola, the director of French production, as his deputy commissioner.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Domville offered to continue on as commissioner for another term after 1984, and his demands were accepted by the board of governors, but chose to leave after Francis Fox declined to accept or deny his renewal.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] After the 1979 election Prime Minister Joe Clark changed the ministry responsible for the NFB from the Secretary of State, which managed it since 1963, to the Minister of Communications, then led by David MacDonald.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] MacDonald supported giving 80% of the sponsored work to private companies and that the NFB only make films that the private companies could not.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Domville offered a three-year phase out of NFB doing sponsored work during a meeting with representatives of the Canadian Film and Television Association and Association des Producteurrs de Films du Quebec in 1979.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] He stated that "sponsored film had become a monkey on the back of English production".
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Encyclopædia Britannica reportedly offered to buy the NFB for $100 million (equivalent to $410,500,000 in 2025) in 1979.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Fox organized the Applebaum-Hébert Committee under the leadership of Louis Applebaum and Jacques Hébert in 1981.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] It was the first review of cultural institutions and policies since the Massey Commission.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The committee released its report on 15 November 1980, in which it called for the elimination of the government's role in producing and distributing cultural products and to instead give it to the private industry.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] They believed that the private industry could create an export market to compete with the United States.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Fox later decided to allow the NFB continue producing content, but ended their involvement in sponsored content, along with their executive production of sponsored work given to private companies.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Domville suggested Patrick Watson as his successor and the board of governors accepted him, but Fox declined as he wanted his Film and Video Policy to be considered by the cabinet first.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Macerola became the acting commissioner of the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Watson was instead appointed to the board of governors and became president of the CBC in 1989.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Macerola left the NFB six months before the expiration of his term in order to join Lavalin in December 1988, and Joan Pennefather became the acting commissioner.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Macerola oversaw a reorganization of the NFB which decreased its distribution offices from twenty-six to twelve and international offices to three.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB attempted to create a television channel in the 1980s.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Marcel Masse gave them permission to attempt to create Young Canada Television (Tèlè-Jeunesse Canada), but the channel failed in June 1987, as the Department of Communications withdrew its financial support leading to the banks to also withdraw their support.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Macerola's Five-Year Operational Plan saw the permanent staff of the NFB fall from 1,085 in 1982, to 728 in 1989, and the amount of work given to freelancers by 1986 was 67% for English productions and 57% for French productions.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB was given an honorary Oscar at the 61st Academy Awards in honour of its fiftieth anniversary.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1990, Wil Champbell and Roger Trottier asked Graydon McCrea about holding a meeting about the participation of First Nations people in the film industry.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB aided in the organization of the Aboriginal Film and Video Symposium in April 1991.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Aboriginal Film and Video Art Alliance (AFVAA) was formed as a result of this meeting.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Studio One, meant for First Nations filmmakers, was formed on 9 June 1991, with a $250,000 budget and under McCrea's supervision.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The studio's first film, *Tlaxwes Wa: Strength of the River*, was released in 1995.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, funding for the studio was ended on 31 March 1996.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] As of 2025, the NFB has made 14,000 productions.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] It has received 78 Oscar nominations, with its 38 nominations for animated shorts placing it behind Disney and MGM in that category.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Norman McLaren founded the NFB's animation unit in 1942, and had George Dunning, René Jodoin, Wolf Koenig, Jean-Paul Ladouceur, Evelyn Lambart, Colin Low, Grant Munro, and Robert Verrall working there within a decade of its creation.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Jodoin organised the NFB's French animated studio in 1966.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] During Derek Lamb's leadership of the English animation studio produced multiple critical acclaimed works, including the Academy Award-winning *Every Child*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Lamb resigned in 1982, and was replaced by Doug McDonald, whose tenure was criticized by animators such as David Fine's statement that "Norman McLaren would be turning in his grave if he knew how the place was being run".
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB's computer animation program was suspended due to budget cuts although the NFB's French animated studio created Peter Foldes's *Metadata* in 1971, and the *Hunger* in 1973.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB returned to computer animation in the 1980s.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB licensed the SANDDE, a system that allows for hand-drawn animation in 3D spaces, from the IMAX Corporation; *Subconscious Password* (2013) was produced using this system.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] As of 2012, the NFB is the only studio with an pinscreen animation screen.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] McLaren used the stop motion technique of pixilation for *Neighbours*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB released StopMo Studio, an app that allowed people to create their own stop motion films, in 2012.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The 3D printing of sets and puppets for stop motion was first used by a NFB film in *Bone Mother*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] *The Girl Who Cried Pearls* (2025) used hand-made puppets in contrast to the standard usage of 3D printing.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Children were rarely featured in NFB films in the early 1940s due to a focus on documentaries related to military efforts.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1943, Grierson increased film production aimed at children for the purpose of education.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The *Ti-Jeans* series, first produced in the 1950s, was the most booked non-theatrical NFB film up until the 1990s. and *Ti-Jean Goes Lumbering* (1953) was the second most popular NFB title according to a 1960 survey.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Films about the socialization of children were produced by the NFB in the 1950s.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Generational gaps and the sexual revolution were depicted in 1966 productions *The Merry-Go-Round*, *The Game*, and *The Shattered Silence*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] NFB productions aimed at children mainly focused on the adults until the 1970s.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] *Sexual Abuse of Children: A Time for Caring* (1979) was the first NFB film to cover child sexual abuse and the amount of films covering child abuse grew in the 1980s.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In the post-war era, the NFB became a pioneer in new developments in documentary film.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB played a key role in both the cinéma vérité and direct cinema movements, working on technical innovations to make its 16 mm synchronized sound equipment more light-weight and portable—most notably the "Sprocketape" portable sound recorder invented for the film board by Ches Beachell in 1955.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Influenced by the work of Henri Cartier-Bresson, the NFB's Studio B production unit experimented with cinema verite in its 1958 *Candid Eye* series.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] *Candid Eye* along with such NFB French-language films as *The Snowshoers (Les Raquetteurs)* (1958) have been credited as helping to inspire the cinéma vérité documentary movement.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Other key cinéma vérité films during this period included *Lonely Boy* (1961) and *Ladies and Gentlemen...
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Running from 1967 to 1980, *Challenge for Change* and its French-language equivalent *Societé Nouvelle* became a global model for the use of film and portable video technology to create community-based participatory documentary films to promote dialogue on local issues and promote social change.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Over two hundred such films were produced, including 27 films about Fogo Island, Newfoundland, directed by Colin Low and early NFB efforts in Indigenous filmmaking, such as Willie Dunn's *The Battle of Crowfoot* (1968).
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Indian Film Crew was an early effort in First Nations filmmaking at the NFB, through its Challenge for Change program, initially proposed by the associate director of the CYC, Jerry Gambill, according to Noel Starblanket.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] George Stoney was brought in as the first executive producer of Challenge for Change.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] It was jointly sponsored by the Company of Young Canadians and the Department of Indian Affairs.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Barbara Wilson, Tom O’Connor, Noel Starblanket, Roy Daniels, Morris Isaac, Willie Dunn, and Mike Kanentakeron Mitchell were on Canada's first all-Indigenous production unit, making groundbreaking work that helped galvanize Indigenous movements across the continent.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] NFB documentarians played a key role in the development of the IMAX film format, following the NFB multi-screen experience *In the Labyrinth*, created for Expo 67 in Montreal.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The film was the centrepiece of a $4.5 million pavilion, which attracted over 1.3 million visitors in 1967, and was co-directed by Roman Kroitor, Colin Low and Hugh O'Connor, and produced by Tom Daly and Kroitor.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] After Expo, Kroitor left the NFB to co-found what would become known as IMAX Corporation, with Graeme Ferguson and Robert Kerr.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In the 1980s, the National Film Board also produced a number of "alternative drama" films, which combined documentary and narrative fiction filmmaking techniques.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Generally starring non-professional actors, these films used a documentary format to present a fictionalized story and were generally scripted by the filmmakers and the cast through a process of improvisation, and are thus classified as docufiction.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] As of March 2013, the NFB devotes one quarter of its production budget to interactive media, including web documentaries.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB is a pioneer in interactive web documentaries, helping to position Canada as a major player in digital storytelling, according to transmedia creator Anita Ondine Smith, as well as Shari Frilot, programmer for Sundance Film Festival's New Frontier program for digital media.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Rob McLaughlin is the executive producer responsible for NFB English-language digital content and strategy, based in the Woodward's Building in Vancouver.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Jeremy Mendes is an interactive artist producing English-language interactive works for the NFB, whose projects include a collaboration with Leanne Allison (*Being Caribou*, *Finding Farley*) on the webdoc *Bear 71*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB is also recognized as a leader in virtual reality, with works such as the Webby Award-winning *The Unknown Photographer*, *Way to Go* and *Cardboard Crash*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In January 2009, the NFB launched its online Screening Room, NFB.ca, offering Canadian and international web users the ability to stream hundreds of NFB films for free as well as embed links in blogs and social sites.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] By mid-2013, the NFB's digital platforms had received approximately 41 million views.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In October 2009, the NFB launched an iPhone application that was downloaded more than 170,000 times and led to more than 500,000 film views in the first four months.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In January 2010, the NFB added high-definition and 3D films to the over 1400 productions available for viewing online.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB introduced a free iPad application in July 2010, followed by its first app for the Android platform in March 2011.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] When the BlackBerry PlayBook launched on April 19, 2011, it included a pre-loaded app offering access to 1,500 NFB titles.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In January 2013, it was announced that the NFB film app would be available for the BlackBerry 10, via the BlackBerry World app store.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In September 2011, the NFB and the Montreal French-language daily *Le Devoir* announced that they would jointly host three interactive essays on their websites, ONF.ca and ledevoir.com.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB is a partner with China's ifeng.com on NFB Zone, the first Canadian-branded web channel in China, with 130 NFB animated shorts and documentary films available on the company's digital platforms.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] NFB documentaries are also available on Netflix Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In April 2013, the NFB announced that it was "seeking commercial partners to establish a subscription service for Internet television and mobile platforms next year.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The plan also sees the NFB building on its relationships with Canadian schools and organizations to create more educational materials about Indigenous peoples in Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] One of the most notable filmmakers in the history of the NFB is Alanis Obomsawin, an Abenaki director who will be completing her 50th film with the NFB in 2017.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In November 2006, the National Film Board of Canada and the Inuit Broadcasting Corporation announced the start of the Nunavut Animation Lab, offering animation training to Nunavut artists.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Films from the Nunavut Animation Lab include Alethea Arnaquq-Baril's 2010 digital animation short *Lumaajuuq*, winner of the Best Aboriginal Award at the Golden Sheaf Awards and named Best Canadian Short Drama at the imagineNATIVE Film + Media Arts Festival.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 2005, the NFB introduced its "First Stories" program for emerging Indigenous directors from Alberta, Saskatchewan and Manitoba.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Twelve five-minute films were produced through the program, with four from each province.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] First Stories was followed by "Second Stories," in which three filmmakers from the previous program—Gerald Auger, Tessa Desnomie and Lorne Olson—were invited back to create 20 minute films.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB was a founding partner in Wapikoni Mobile, a mobile film and media production unit for emerging First Nations filmmakers in Quebec.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Still Photography Division of the Canadian Government Motion Picture Bureau was transferred to the NFB on 8 August 1941; this occurred two months after the rest of the organization was absorbed into the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Still Photography Division of the Wartime Information Board was acquired by the NFB in 1943.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Nicholas Morant, George Hunter, and Ronny Jaques were employed by the Still Photography Division during World War II.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1944, the Still Photography Division started charging a below-standard fee for reproductions.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The Commercial and Press Photographers' Association of Canada accused the division of unfair competition due to this.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1946, the NFB changed its policies to match the standard rate of $2.50 for newspapers and $5 for magazines.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The 1950 National Film Act included photography under the NFB's purview.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Employment in the division fell by 20% from 1945 to 1946, and declined from 70 employees in 1945, to 22 by 1952.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The division had to rely on freelancers.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The division was placed under Technical Services in 1951.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The photography division did not participate in the move to Saint-Laurent due to objections from the External Affairs, Trade and Commerce, the Travel Bureau, and other federal agencies that relied on it for promotional services.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1971, two-thirds of the photography division's employees were moved to Information Canada and its photographic archive was diverted into the Library and Archives Canada and Photothèque, the commercial image bank of Information Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] However, Information Canada was eliminated in 1975, and the images in Photothèque were returned to the NFB in 1976.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1985, the division was turned into the Canadian Museum of Contemporary Photography.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] 250,000 photos were created by the division during its existence, with 25,000 being taken during World War II.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The NFB has been a leader in films by women, with the world's first publicly funded women's film's studio, Studio D, followed subsequently by its French-language equivalent, Studio des femmes.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Beginning on March 8, 2016, International Women's Day, the NFB began introducing a series of gender parity initiatives.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 1974, in conjunction with International Women's Year, the NFB created Studio D on the recommendation of long-time employee Kathleen Shannon.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Shannon was designated as executive director of the new studio—the first government-funded film studio dedicated to women filmmakers in the world—which became one of the NFB's most celebrated filmmaking units, winning awards and breaking distribution records.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Notable films produced by the studio include three Academy Award-winning documentaries *I'll Find a Way* (1977), *If You Love This Planet* (1982) and *Flamenco at 5:15* (1983), as well as *Not a Love Story* (1982) and *Forbidden Love: The Unashamed Stories of Lesbian Lives* (1992).
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Studio D was shut down in 1996, amidst a sweeping set of federal government budget cuts, which impacted the NFB as a whole.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] As of March 8, 2016, researchers and librarians at the University of Calgary announced an archival project to preserve records of Studio D.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] On March 8, 2016, NFB head Claude Joli-Coeur announced a new gender-parity initiative, with the NFB committing that half of all its production spending will be earmarked for films directed by women.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] The following year, the NFB announced that it also plans to achieve gender balance by 2020 in such creative positions as editing, scriptwriting, musical composition, cinematography and artistic direction.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] As of 2017, 53% of its producers and executive producers are women, as well as half of its administrative council.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] While it is claiming success, directing credits and budget shares have barely changed.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 2016–2017, 44 per cent of NFB productions were directed by women (compared to 51 per cent directed by men and five per cent by mixed teams).
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Budget-wise, 43 per cent of production funds were given to projects led by women (vs.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] 40 per cent to projects directed by men and 15 per cent to ones overseen by mixed teams).
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In 2018–2019, 48% of NFB works were directed by women (38% by men and 14% by mixed teams), and 44% of the NFB production budget was allocated to works created by women (41% for works by men and 15% for works by mixed teams).
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Production personnel are between 10 and 25%.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Hothouse, a program for emerging animators that marked its tenth anniversary in 2015.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Notable Hothouse alumni include Academy Award nominee Patrick Doyon, part of its 2006 edition.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Cinéaste recherché(e) is a similar program for French-language emerging animators.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] Past graduates include Michèle Cournoyer, who took part in the program's 9th edition in 1989.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] A collaboration with the Canadian Film Centre on a theatrical documentary development program.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] First launched in January 2009, the program has led to the production of Sarah Polley’s *Stories We Tell*, Yung Chang‘s *The Fruit Hunters* and Su Rynard's *The Messenger*.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p01] In May 2015, the CFC and NFB announced a new version of the program entitled the NFB/CFC Creative Doc Lab.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] As part of the 2012 budget cuts, the NFB announced that it was forced to close its Toronto Mediatheque and Montreal CineRobotheque public facilities.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] They ceased to operate as of September 1, 2012.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] In September 2013, the University of Quebec in Montreal (Université du Québec à Montréal) announced that it had acquired the CineRobotheque for its communications faculty.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] As stipulated in the *National Film Act* of 1950, the person who holds the position of Government Film Commissioner is the head of the NFB.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] As of 2022, the 17th commissioner of the NFB is Suzanne Guèvremont, who will also be the chairperson for a five-year term.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] Before Guèvremont, the 16th commissioner of the NFB was Claude Joli-Coeur, who led the NFB for nearly nine years and was the agency's longest serving commissioner joining first in 2003 under Jacques Bensimon.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] Jolie-Coeur also served as interim commissioner from 2006 to 2007 under Tom Perlmutter.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] Over the years, the NFB has been internationally recognized with more than 5000 film awards.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] In 2009, Norman McLaren's *Neighbours* was added to UNESCO's Memory of the World Programme, listing the most significant documentary heritage collections in the world.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] In addition to *Neighbours*, other NFB productions have been the source of controversy, including two NFB productions broadcast on CBC Television that criticized the role of Canadians in wartime led to questions in the Senate of Canada.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] In the early 1970s, two Quebec political documentaries, Arcand's *On est au coton* and Gilles Groulx's *24 heures ou plus*, were initially withheld from release by the NFB due to controversial content.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] A decade later, *The Valour and the Horror* outraged some when it suggested that there was incompetence on the part of Canadian military command, and that Canadian soldiers had committed unprosecuted war crimes against German soldiers.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] The series became the subject of an inquiry by the Senate.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] Other controversial productions included the 1981 film *Not a Love Story: A Film About Pornography*, a 1981 Studio D documentary critiquing pornography that was itself banned in the province of Ontario on the basis of pornographic content.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] Released the following year, *If You Love This Planet*, winner of the Academy Award for Best Live Action Short, was labelled foreign propaganda under the Foreign Agents Registration Act of 1938 in the United States.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] The NFB is a minority owner of the Canadian digital television channel Documentary Channel.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] The NFB-branded series *Retrovision* aired on VisionTV along with the French-language *Carnets ONF* series on APTN.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] Moreover, in 1997, the American cable channel Cartoon Network created a weekly 30-minute show called *O Canada*, which specifically showcased a compilation of NFB-produced works; the segment was later discontinued in favour of Adult Swim.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] The Board's logo consists of a standing stylized figure (originally green) with its arms wide upward (designed similarly to the CBS logo).
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] The arms are met by an arch that mirrors them.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] The round head in between then resembles a pupil, making the entire symbol appear to be an eye with legs.
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] Launched in 1968, the logo symbolized a vision of humanity and was called "Man Seeing / L'homme qui voit".
[src:cinema-politica/national-film-board-p02] It was updated in 2003 by the firm of Paprika Communications.
